title.narrative: 102 IMMUNIZATION AND OTHER COMMON CHILDHOOD ILLNESSES

description.narrative: By 2022, government and partners have institutional capacity to ensure pregnant women, infants and children from marginalized and at risk groups, especially the girl child have equitable availability, access, knowledge and demand for quality health care services for immunization as well as prevention and treatment of other childhood illnesses including pneumonia, diarrhoea, malaria and paediatric HIV, in selected states., which contributes to Fast-Track The End Of Hiv/Aids, Health And Development In Early Childhood And Adolescence, Immunization Services As Part Of Primary Health Care, Strengthening Primary Health Care And High-Impact Health Interventions. UNICEF aims to achieve this through Advocacy And Communications, Advocacy And Public Engagement, Community Engagement, Social And Behaviour Change, Developing And Leveraging Resources And Partnerships, Evaluations, Research And Data, Fostering Innovation And Use Of New Technologies, Harnessing Power Of Business And Markets, Systems Strengthening And Institution Building, Systems Strengthening To Leave No One Behind, United Nations Working Together. This contributes to the following Country Programme result: Business and Key Business Stakeholders demonstrate growing willingness, commitment and resource allocation for protecting and promoting child rights in policy and practice by 2022

description.narrative: UNICEF continued to bridge the equity-gaps through special strategies in 15 tribal predominant states. Significant strides were made for cold-chain strengthening by procurement and installation of equipment in 24 states, capacity-building, supportive-supervision and EVM conduction; 77% of Primary-Health-Centers in UNICEF supported-states were designated as cold-chain-point for immunization; UNICEF supported the MOHFW in sustaining focus on RI post-second wave of COVID-19 pandemic through advocacy, capacity building and demand generation. UNICEF supported in developing operational & guidelines, awareness generation materials and for Intensified-Diarrhoea-Control Fortnight and ongoing anti-pneumonia. | Status:Partially met | As-of Date:04/01/2022
